Comfycreations here, with a sixth chapter of qt kangaroo goodness for you guys. Really sorry it took me so long to get this update done, but after all the delays I hope the length and content of the update makes up for it.

43.2k word update for A Roo'd Awakening starting on line 2113.
Full story at this pastebin: https://pastebin.com/muScjRyj
Pastebin with all story related art can be found here: https://pastebin.com/YLvs3CTQ

As always, I appreciate any and all feedback/criticism of any kind and length, whether positive or negative as it's helped me identify issues with my writing in the past. Thanks in advance to all my readers, I hope you guys enjoy this update as much as I enjoyed writing it for you. There is a question I have for any readers, which might affect the speed at which I get future updates out. I've been wanting to touch up the first four chapters of the story for a long time and turn them from greentext into prose, so I'm wondering if you guys would rather I just do that all at once now and get it out of the way in exchange for quicker future updates or just continue updating normally and pick away at it over time? I would greatly appreciate any input or feedback on this, but rest assured that me touching up the story and turning it to prose will in no way affect or change current or past plot points.

I'd like to also thank a few people for helping make this update possible. Firstly, I'd like to thank idontwantthis for his help with providing crucial feedback, help with story direction, story ideas, proofreading/beta reading and so much more that I can't even adequately put into words. Secondly, I'd like to give a special thanks to somethingaboutsharks for also helping me come up with ideas, assisting in proofreading and also providing valuable feedback on the update while I was writing. And finally, thank you to Tious for beta reading and helping spot some last minute mistakes and changes I needed to make.

Anonymous Sun 02 Jun 2019 01:37:53 No.23489866 Report
Quoted By: >>23491089
>>23479341
>question I have for any readers
> been wanting to touch up the first four chapters of the story for a long time and turn them from greentext into prose
1)
> just do that all at once now and get it out of the way in exchange for quicker future updates
2)
> or just continue updating normally and pick away at it over time?

I'd go with option 2) for Reasons.

You've reached a solid level of writing and good momentum & rhythm for the story at this point. Don't interrupt that. If you're comfortable with current output, don't interrupt that with a forced break. It will be harder to gain back momentum & pacing.

Also, your current style is still improving, so no need to revisit earlier work and catch it up to your current style. Rather, let your current style reach equilibrium and then go back and polish all the earlier work for consistency with where you are after maybe (?) Ch 8. Or so.

Caveat: USUALLY.

Because, maybe you are ready for a break and want to revisit the old stuff. It would give you a chance to immerse yourself in the original writing and make tweaks you feel are needed. Maybe a few items are required to support what you wrote later. Don't fear minor retcons if they are truly necessary, but minimize them when and where possible.

Decide for yourself if you're on a roll. Only you know your own mental space. If you're on fire, forge ahead. Get the next chapter or three out of your head before going back and integrating everything.

But if you're feeling some burnout coming on, pace yourself with a break of some sort. That can be a short hiatus or it can be going back and polishing up earlier work. That's not a black or white decision. You can do some polishing and continue the current story at a slower pace if that feels like a better balance.

Crawl inside your own head for a bit and decide what's best for yourself. Ask for further feedback if you think that can help.

And: Thank you! Fun read.

Not him; I've said this before: never start revising until you're done. Don't do it. Whether your story is 5k words long or over 100k, don't draft a revision strategy until your story is written. Revision is another animal entirely and generally requires more time than writing the first draft itself. Just remember that your story is a DRAFT and isn't finished until you've combed the completed thing multiple times over. Writing for a thread doesn't have the same feeling, but think of us as your test audience. Revise chapter by chapter later, not while you're writing, it will stultify your work and stymie said story.

>>23491089
No prob. Glad to try & support content creators whenever possible. Hope my thoughts do more good than harm.

This: >>23494705 is also valid. I would argue the Devil is in the details a bit, though.

I'm not backing off anything I said earlier, but one post can hardly contain all possibilities. It's a valid concern that attempting to enter a revision cycle too early can create an endless loop of never finishing anything, too many alternates are spawned & added complexity starts to make things too overwhelming to track all changes & possibilities. I partially addressed this by suggesting that you not begin revising ... YET.

But a balance can be struck, especially when earlier work is in an unfinished state or some glaring changes are required. You can be taking notes on what you feel needs to be addressed, as well as maintain a feedback file from readers. This is more 'preparation for revision' rather than actually re-writing earlier work.

As you've moved forward with the story, there are things you have already written and ideas that intend to incorporate into future chapters. Polishing up inconsistencies is valid work, even if you don't publish it immediately. Keep an open mind when you require changes because they're really needed, or when you just want to hack something else in.

The intent of my orig post was: Yes, you _can_ do some revision if you really feel it's needed or you need to switch gears for a break. However, get the story finished or 'mostly finished' before diving too deep. The final chapter doesn't have to be polished & complete; you just need to have the endgame of the story solidly outlined and in sight. It's valid to revise earlier chapters at that point because that act of revision may well affect how you write & wrap up the final chapter(s).

Right now you're still in draft mode, with your readers helping to identify dependencies and deficiencies. How many chapters do you think you will have with the finished product?

Anonymous Sun 02 Jun 2019 10:01:06 No.23498077 Report
Quoted By: >>23499311
>>23491089
>>23494705
>never start revising until you're done
While that _can_ be a valid position, I'd suggest that "never" is an awfully strong word. There are certainly occasions an situations where going back and addressing issues with earlier parts of a work _can_ be necessary.

In this case, keep in mind that the first four chapters are all in greentext format. The bulk of what Comfycreations was addressing here is converting that greentexted portion into prose. Along the way he(?) would naturally be performing cleanup operations, including glaring errors and revisions.

As you noted, the entire story is still in draft mode, although the most recent stuff is less so. It's valid to take a hard look at what that project is going to look like and map it out, at least. As I mentioned here >>23497888, the act of diving into those earlier chapters will clarify and affect what was written later, and what still remains to be written.

I asked teh question: how many chapters remaining? The actual number & structure of the remaining story isn't the core of that question. I'm really asking if you have the endgame of the story outlined and laid out. If it is, and it's better than ~90% all in position at this point, the potential harm of diving into the earlier chapters is greatly reduced.

But, if you really have a lot left to iron out for the remaining story, you aren't ready for major revisions to the early chapters. If you get stuck, need a break, suffer some writer's block, then converting that greentext into prose may be the exercise required to break through a sticking point and be able to continue & finish.
